[[Image:PittsburghOperaBuilding.jpg|thumb|260px|right|Pittsburgh Opera Building located in the former George Westinghouse Air Brake Factory at 2425 Liberty Avenue in the Strip District of Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania]]
'''Pittsburgh Opera''' is an [[United States|American]] [[opera]] company based in [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania|Pittsburgh]], [[Pennsylvania]].  It is one of two opera companies in the city, the other being Opera Theatre of Pittsburgh.  Pittsburgh Opera gives performances in several venues, primarily at the [[Benedum Center]], with other performances at the [[Pittsburgh Creative and Performing Arts School]] Theater. [http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/s_592946.html Pittsburgh Opera headquarters] is located in the former [[George Westinghouse]] [[Westinghouse Air Brake Company|Air Brake]] Factory, 2425 Liberty Avenue, in the [[Strip District]]. Pittsburgh Opera has applied for LEED certification and expects to be the first [http://www.pittsburghopera.org/pages/green-initiative "green" opera company] in the U.S. upon its certification in 2010. 

Pittsburgh Opera was established in [[1939]] as the Pittsburgh Opera Company and is the eighth-oldest opera company in the United States. The company was founded by five women who established the Pittsburgh Opera Society in 1939, making possible the inaugural performance of [[Jacques Offenbach|Offenbach]]'s ''[[Les Contes d'Hoffmann]]'' at the [[Carnegie Music Hall]] in March, 1940.<ref>[http://www.pittsburghopera.org/company/history.shtml?search=history=F000 Pittsburgh Opera<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>  The first director of the company was Richard Karp, from 1942 to 1977.  His daughter Barbara Karp took over her father's duties during his final illness.  James DeBlasis then served as interim artistic director after the resignation of Barbara Karp.  In 1983, [[Tito Capobianco]] became Pittsburgh Opera's general director, holding this position until 1997.<ref name="Croan1">{{cite news | author=Robert Croan | title=Weinstein to take helm at Opera | url=http://www.post-gazette.com/magazine/19990504opera6.asp | work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette | date=4 May 1999 | accessdate=2007-12-05}}</ref>  From 1997 to 2000, Capobianco was the company's artistic director, before leaving in 2000.<ref>{{cite news | author=Robert Croan | title='The Illustrated History of Opera in Pittsburgh: The Pittsburgh Opera Story' by Hax McCullough | url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/05282/584613-148.stm | work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette | date=9 October 2005 | accessdate=2007-10-06}}</ref>

Mark Weinstein became general director of Pittsburgh Opera in 1999, after starting as executive director in 1997.<ref name="Croan1"/>  During his tenure, he presided over an increase in the company's endowment from US $4 million to US $16 million, as well as the retirement of US $2.5 million in debt.<ref>{{cite news | author=Mark Kanny | title=RiverParc development will force relocation of opera | url=http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/living/arts/opera/s_499095.html | work=Pittsburgh Tribune Review | date=23 March 2007 | accessdate=2007-10-06}}</ref>  Weinstein also presided over the addition of an extra production during the company season, 5 productions as opposed to 4, from the 2001-2002 season to the 2003-2004 season.<ref>{{cite news | author=Mark Kanny | title=Leadership changes may take opera to its next step | url=http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/living/arts/opera/s_537217.html | work=Pittsburgh Tribune Review | date=11 November 2007 | accessdate=2007-12-05}}</ref>  In October 2007, Weinstein announced his resignation as Pittsburgh Opera's general director to become executive director at [[Washington National Opera]], effective February 1, 2008.<ref>{{cite news | author=Andrew Druckenbrod | title=Pittsburgh Opera's chief leaving for D.C. | url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/07302/829345-388.stm | work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette | date=29 October 2007 | accessdate=2007-12-05}}</ref> After a six-month international search, Artistic Director Christopher Hahn was appointed [http://www.redorbit.com/news/technology/1452015/pittsburgh_opera_appoints_christopher_hahn_its_general_director/index.html General Director] in June 2008.

South Africa native [http://www.pittsburghopera.org/pages/leadership Christopher Hahn] served as the company's artistic director from 2000 until his appointment as General Director. [[John Mauceri]] was Music Director of Pittsburgh Opera from 2000 until his resignation in 2006, to take up an academic post in North Carolina.<ref>{{cite news | author=Robert Croan | title=Opera's music director to lead North Carolina School of the Arts | url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/06133/689693-42.stm | work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette | date=13 May 2006 | accessdate=2007-10-06}}</ref>  In October 2006, [http://www.wolvertonartists.com/artists/walker/walker_bio.php Antony Walker] was named the next Music Director of Pittsburgh Opera, and assumed the post immediately.<ref>{{cite news | author=Mark Kanny | title=Pittsburgh Opera names music director | url=http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/living/arts/opera/s_474523.html | work=Pittsburgh Tribune Review | date=12 October 2006 | accessdate=2007-10-06}}</ref>  Walker's initial contract was for 3 years, but has since been extended through the 2011-12 season.<ref>{{cite news | author=Andrew Druckenbrod | title=Pittsburgh Opera welcomes young Aussie as its new music director | url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/06285/729338-42.stm | work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette | date=12 October 2006 | accessdate=2007-10-06}}</ref>
On April 1, 2008, in a performance of Verdi's "Aida" at the Benedum Center, Music Director Antony Walker stepped in to sing the role of Radames in the final act of the opera at the same time as conducting, while the tenor acted the role on stage.<ref>{{cite news | author=Andrew Druckenbrod | title=Conductor does double duty as tenor loses voice | url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/08093/869798-388.stm | work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette | date=2 April 2008 | accessdate=2008-04-02}}</ref>

==Music Directors==
* Theo Alcantara
* [[John Mauceri]] (2000-2006)
* Antony Walker (2006-present)

